{
  "text": "The pathological mechanisms described above are similar to those observed in the retina. As in the kidney, the high blood sugar exerts deleterious effects on the retina, which include the apoptosis of Muller cells, ganglion cells [CITATION_1] , and pericytes, the thickening of the capillary basement membrane, and the proliferation of endothelial cells in the retina. These effects lead to pathological changes in DR, including nonperfusive capillaries, the appearance of microaneurysms, and exudation. Hence, GFR not only may be an important clinical marker for DN, but also could be correlated with DR.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "35985628"
